article.description: It's not exactly Magic, but it's a stunner nonetheless: Orlando has a two-game winning streak.
article.headline: Magic's Williams drops season-high 17 points
article.linkText: Magic beat Wizards for first win streak of season
article.story: WASHINGTON (AP) -- It's not exactly Magic, but it's a stunner nonetheless: Orlando has a two-game winning streak. The team that began the week with a 19-game losing streak got 27 points from Tracy McGrady and a season-high 17 from Shammond Williams to defeat the Washington Wizards 95-91 Wednesday night. Williams made three 3-pointers and hit two clinching free throws with 8.1 seconds left for Orlando, which snapped an eight-game road losing streak. "It's been a while since we've been on a streak on the winning side," McGrady said. "I guess it took that 19-game losing streak for us to realize that we could be a pretty good team if we could all stay focused and execute on both ends of the court." Larry Hughes scored 19 and Kwame Brown had 18 for Washington, which lost for the sixth time in eight games. Point guard Gilbert Arenas, wearing a road jersey, blue sweats and a headband instead of street clothes, sat out his eighth straight game yet still found a way to hurt his team from the bench. He was called for two technical fouls and ejected with 1.4 seconds left in the first quarter after saying something to official Bernie Fryer. "He's young. He was in it, you can't fault him for that," Washington coach Eddie Jordan said about the lapse in judgment. "It was a mistake, but I thought the official had a quick whistle with the second one." Rookie Steve Blake made a 3-pointer with 2:39 to play to bring Washington within 93-91, and the offenses for both teams vanished. The two free throws by Williams in the closing seconds were the only points after Blake's 3-pointer. The Wizards, who turned the ball over 20 times, had two possessions to tie the game, but Hughes and Juan Dixon both missed jumpers. "It's tough because we were playing pretty good defense down the stretch," Blake said. "This is one you really want to get because you feel like you have a chance to win. It would have been big for us." After McGrady missed on a drive to the basket, the Wizards had one last chance to tie. But Christian Laettner missed an open jumper and Dixon lost a jump ball to Zaza Pachulia, who tipped the ball to Williams in the closing seconds. McGrady, who scored 12 points in the first quarter despite a disastrous attempt at an early dunk, hit consecutive 3-pointers in the third quarter to give the Magic its 11-point lead at 68-57. "That's what we need because I can get it going at any given time," McGrady said. "It was good for my team to start knocking down shots and making plays to help us out because those guys did start loading up on me." Dixon, who finished with 15, sparked an 11-2 third-quarter run with three field goals and an assist to help the Wizards pull to 73-72 with 2:04 left. However, two mistakes by Hughes in the closing seconds of the quarter let the Magic build their lead to six points. Game Notes: Orlando's Juwan Howard, Rod Strickland and Tyron Lue all used to play for the Wizards, while Washington's roster has former Magic players Brendan Haywood and Chris Whitney. ... The Wizards are now 0-4 against the Atlantic Division, which only has one team with a winning record. ... Dixon grabbed a career-high seven rebounds.
